	Pak players undergo dope tests  Karachi: Twenty six Pakistani cricketers among the 30 probables for the Champions Trophy, including captain Shoaib Malik and Shoaib Akhtar, underwent dope tests conducted by the World Anti-Doping Agency (Wada) representatives in Lahore on Sunday. The dope samples would be sent to an International Olympic Committee-accredited laboratory in Malaysia and the results are expected in 10 days, a top Pakistan Cricket Board (PCB) official said. ldquo;The samples were taken by Wada accredited personnel and we expect the results in about 10 days, not before that, rdquo; Dr Sohail Saleem, a member of PCB rsquo;s medical commission, said.    
	 PCB move  Karachi: With indiscipline among players becoming a major headache for the Pakistan Cricket Board (PCB), it has decided to hire former batsman Moin-ul Atiq to help in character building of youngsters enrolled at its national and regional cricket academies. Moin, who played five one-day Internationals for Pakistan, has a masters degree in sports management. ldquo;My job is to basically give lectures to the players the theme of which is character building and how to be positive about the game and their future plans, rdquo; Moin said. He said the board had initiated the programme as it was felt there was a need to educate and groom young players.    
	 Malik rsquo;s view  Karachi: Pakistan captain Shoaib Malik has welcomed Shoaib Akhtar rsquo;s return, saying the maverick pacer is a proven match-winner and would give the team rsquo;s attack the much-needed boost. Shoaib has been included in the 30-member probables list for the Champions Trophy.     
	 Dave visit  Colombo: ICC general manager (cricket) Dave Richardson will be here next week to inspect the infrastructure that has been put in place to operationalise the umpire referral system which goes on trial during the India-Sri Lanka Test series. The system will allow cricketers to challenge the umpire rsquo;s decision to obviate controversies and bring in greater transparency in the game.    
	 Shane rsquo;s charity  Melbourne: Moved by the plight of Jaipur rsquo;s street children, Australian allrounder Shane Watson has associated himself with a Sydney-based charity to raise funds for their rehabilitation. The 27-year-old, who with his all-round performance helped Rajasthan Royals to the inaugural Indian Premier League title, came up with the initiative after he was shocked to learnt that the city has 500,000 street children. To initiate the process, Watson has decided to host a fund-raising dinner mdash; a night in Rajasthan mdash; on August 2 at Sydney rsquo;s Shangri-La hotel, where he will share his experiences of his stay in Jaipur.
                                                                                                                                                               
